						<div class="list-group-item">

							<h2 class="list-group-item-heading">Releiving Pressure on the Powerplay</h2>

							<p>In this example the opposition is being aggressive and pressuring the puck hard on the powerplay. It is important that everyone knows what's going to happen in this situation.</p>

							<p>FWD #2 pressure's Red, FWD #1 takes away Teal, D #4 takes away Green, and D# 3 takes away Yellow. Blue is the open man, but with Red being pressured, the passing lanes have been cut off and the pass from Red to Blue becomes a high risk play.</p>

							<p>To releive pressure, Red rims the puck around the boards to Blue. Blue should be anticipating this play when the penalty killers are being that aggressive.</p>

							<p>When the puck gets to Blue, we are now set up in our umbrella powerplay on the other side of the ice. Also note that the defense is now all caught on one side of the ice, forcing them to scramble to get back into position.</p>

							<div align="center">
								<%= link_to asset_path('pp-umbrella-low-slot-pressure.gif'),target: '_blank' do %>
								<%= image_tag 'pp-umbrella-low-slot-pressure.gif',class: 'img-responsive' %>
								<% end %>
							</div>

							<h4>Notes</h4>

							<p>Notice how when Red is being pressured, and D #4 decides to take away Green. Green then moves towards the slot area slightly. This keeps D #4 out of the passing lane for Red to rim around to Blue. <b>Green should not move below the goaline if D #4 decides to take away Green.</b></p>

							<p>Also note how Yellow stars close to the net as the puck is high in the zone. As the puck moves lower in the zone, Yellow moves higher in the slot, away from the net, to create an angle for a one-T from Red or Green. When the puck is high, Yellow trys to screen the goalie. When the puck is low, Yellow moves to create an angle for a one-T near the slot.</p>

